\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
A New Optimal Frame ALOHA Utilizing the Time-Aware Efficiency for RFID Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Calculating the optimal frame length in Frame Slotted ALOHA anti-collision
 algorithm in RFID systems is a critical issue to achieve the maximum reading
 efficiency.
 Previous studies have focused mainly on the conventional definitions of
 the reading efficiency, which is the ratio between the number of successful
 slots and the total number of slots (frame length).
 However the efficient RFID readers can identify the type of a slot either
 it is idle, successful, or collided slot, and consequently it can control
 the slot duration.
 This property is utilized to use a more accurate metric (Time-Aware Framed
 Slotted ALOHA (TAFSA) efficiency), which considers the differences in the
 slot durations.
 In this letter a novel optimal Time-Aware fame length equation is defined
 using the TAFSA efficiency.
 This new Time-Aware frame length is derived analytically and numerically.
 Simulation results indicate 10% saving in the reading time using the proposed
 Time-Aware frame length instead of using the conventional frame length
 for different ISO 18000-6C anti-collision algorithms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
INTRODUCTION
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the recent years, the number of applications that use Radio-Frequency
 Identification Systems (RFID) has increased, and the reading speed became
 one of the most critical issues in these applications.
 RFID networks consist of: 1) Readers (Interrogators), which are responsible
 of scanning the interrogation area and identifying the tags.
 2) Tags (Transponders), which store the data to be read by the readers.
 In RFID systems, tags share a common communication channel, so the probability
 of tag-collision increases in dense networks.
 Since passive tags are the most practical tags in the market because of
 their low price and simple design, they cannot sense the channel or communicate
 with the others.
 In this type of networks, readers are responsible of coordinating the network
 and avoid the collisions using different anti-collision algorithms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Depending on previous published RFID work, anti-collision algorithms can
 be divided into two main classes: a) Deterministic algorithms which are
 Tree based 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tree1,Tree2"

\end_inset

.
 b) Probabilistic algorithms which are Frame Slotted Aloha (FSA) based 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aloha1,Aloha2_Floerkemeier,Aloha3_florke,Aloha4_Vogt"

\end_inset

.
 FSA is the most widely used in RFID standards due to its simplicity and
 robustness.
 In FSA, the communication timing between the reader and the tags is divided
 into frames, each frame includes a specific number of slots.
 The conventional definition of the slot is the time starting from the reader
 command to the tags in the interrogation region till receiving a reply
 from the tags.
 There are three types of slots: 1) Successful Slot: In this slot, only
 one tag chooses this slot and is fully identified, and then deactivated
 by the reader.
 2) Collided Slot: Here more than one tag reply which cause collision and
 the reader cannot identify any of them.
 3) Idle Slot: In this slot type, the reader does not receive any reply
 from the tags.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the Random Access Theory, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 number of tags, the distribution of these tags in each frame 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DFSA_shoute_Random"

\end_inset

, by the following equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=L\left(1-\frac{1}{L}\right)^{n},\, S=n\left(1-\frac{1}{L}\right)^{n-1},\, C=L-E-S\label{eq: number of slot definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\size default

\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $E,\, S,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 are respectively the number of idle, successful, and collided slots per
 frame.
 The conventional definition of the reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DFSA_shoute_Random"

\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta=\frac{number\, of\, successful\, slots\,(S)}{Frame\, length\,(L)}\label{eq:eff basic equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main goal of FSA algorithm is to find the optimal value of the frame
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which maximizes the reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, based on the equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: number of slot definition"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eff basic equ"

\end_inset

.This result in the equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta=\frac{n}{L}\left(1-\frac{1}{L}\right)^{n-1}\label{eq:eff calss f(L)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eff calss f(L)"

\end_inset

, the reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is maximized when 
\begin_inset Formula $L=n$
\end_inset

 as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DFSA_shoute_Random"

\end_inset

.
 All these calculations are correct if and only if the FSA has identical
 slot durations.
 However, in the RFID standards (e.g 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "standard"

\end_inset

), the slot duration depends on the the type of the slot idle, successful,
 or collided slot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper a novel method for calculating the optimal frame length using
 a Time-Aware reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{TA}$
\end_inset

 is proposed.
 In this Time-Aware reading efficiency, the different slot durations are
 considered.
 The optimal frame size is analytically and numerically analyzed.
 Simulation results are applied on the ISO 18000-6C standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "standard"

\end_inset

 emphasize that the new frame size results an improved performance and decreases
 the reading time compared to the conventional frame size.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper organized as follows: In Section II the proposed new optimal
 frame length using Time-Aware FSA efficiency is presented.
 In section III numerical analysis for the Time-Aware optimal frame length
 is applied that is suitable for practical applications.
 In section IV the new optimum frame size is applied on the ISO 18000-6C
 Standard.
 Finally In section V numerical results are presented, before we conclude
 in section VI.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
NEW OPTIMAL FRAME LENGTH UNDER VARIABLE SLOT DURATION
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To calculate the proposed optimal Time-Aware frame size 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{_{opt-TA}}$
\end_inset

, which takes into consideration the differences between the slot durations,
 we have to define first the Time-Aware reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{_{TA}}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\eta_{_{TA}} & = & \frac{Successful\, Time}{Total\, Reading\, Time}=\frac{T_{s}}{T_{e}+T_{s}+T_{c}}\label{eq:eff timing simple}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{e}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 are respectively the total idle, successful, and collided times per frame.
 They can be expressed as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
T_{s} & = & S\cdot t_{s}\nonumber \\
T_{e} & = & E\cdot t_{e}\label{eq:timing equ}\\
T_{c} & = & C\cdot t_{c}\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 are respectively defined as the number of successful, idle, and collided
 slots.
 furthermore 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{e},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{c}$
\end_inset

 are respectively the successful, idle, and collided slot durations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eff timing simple"

\end_inset

, the definition of the Time-Aware reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{_{TA}}$
\end_inset

 is the ratio between the successful time and the total reading time of
 a frame.
 The Time-Aware reading efficiency calculations are not only based on the
 number of slots, but also take into consideration the temporal duration
 of slots.
 From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:timing equ"

\end_inset

, the successful time 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{s}$
\end_inset

 of a frame is the product of the number of successful slots 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in a frame by the successful slot duration 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly the idle 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{e}$
\end_inset

 and collided 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 time of a frame are respectively the product of the number of idle and
 collided slots 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 in a frame by the idle and collided slot duration 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{e}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eff timing simple"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:timing equ"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{_{TA}}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{_{TA}}=\frac{t_{s}S}{t_{e}E+t_{s}S+t_{c}C}\label{eq:eff-semi_simple}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step is to drive a new optimum frame length 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{opt-TA}$
\end_inset

 under the Time-Aware environment.
 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{opt-TA}$
\end_inset

 can be optimized by finding the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which maximize the Time-Aware reading efficiency.
 This is achieved by differentiating the reading efficiency in equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eff-semi_simple"

\end_inset

 with respect to the frame length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and equate the result to zero: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta\eta_{_{TA}}}{\delta L}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: number of slot definition"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 , and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 are function of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, however 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{e}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{s},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{c}$
\end_inset

 are constants, so the equation can be simplified as shown in the below
 equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{(t_{e}E+t_{s}S+t_{c}C)t_{s}\frac{\delta}{\delta L}(S)-t_{s}S\frac{\delta}{\delta L}(t_{e}E+t_{s}S+t_{c}C)}{(t_{e}E+t_{s}S+t_{c}C)^{2}}=0
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After multiplying both sides by the denominator and divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{s}$
\end_inset

 as it is non zero constant, the equation can be simplified: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(t_{e}E+t_{s}S+t_{c}C)\frac{\delta}{\delta L}(S)=S\frac{\delta}{\delta L}(t_{e}E+t_{s}S+t_{c}C)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(t_{e}E+t_{c}C)\frac{\delta}{\delta L}(S)+t_{s}S\frac{\delta}{\delta L}(S)=S\frac{\delta}{\delta L}(t_{e}E+t_{c}C)+t_{s}S\frac{\delta}{\delta L}S
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After subtracting the term which multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{s},$
\end_inset

 the equation results in:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(t_{e}E+t_{c}C)\frac{\delta}{\delta L}(S)=S\frac{\delta}{\delta L}(t_{e}E+t_{c}C)\label{eq:simple differentiation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then substituting by the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 , and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: number of slot definition"

\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:simple differentiation"

\end_inset

 and simplifying the result, the exact equation for the proposed Time-Aware
 frame length is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(1-\frac{n}{L_{_{opt-TA}}}\right)=\left(1-C_{t}\right)\left(1-\frac{1}{L_{_{opt-TA}}}\right)^{n}\label{eq:Lopt comlex expresion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Lopt_vs_Ct.emf
	lyxscale 20
	scale 12

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $L_{opt-TA}$
\end_inset

 versus slot duration constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=100$
\end_inset

 tags 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Frame size ct"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of tags and the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the ratio between the idle slot duration and the collided slot duration,
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}=\frac{t_{e}}{t_{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lopt comlex expresion"

\end_inset

 shows the exact relations between the proposed Time-Aware frame length
 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{opt-TA}$
\end_inset

 and the number of tags 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, which takes into consideration the time difference in the slot durations.
 The value of the optimal time aware frame length is affected by the slot
 durations as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increasing the value of the idle slot durations with respect to the collided
 slot durations (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 increases), the reading efficiency will be decreased due to the increase
 in the total idle time per frame.
 The value of the optimal frame length should be decreased to compensate
 this decrease in the reading efficiency and keep on working with maximum
 efficiency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increasing the collided slot durations with respect to the idle slot durations
 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 decreases), the reading efficiency will be decreased due to the increase
 in the total collided time per frame, and the value of the optimal frame
 length should be increased to compensate this decrease at the reading efficienc
y.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Changing the successful slot durations with respect to the collided and
 idle slot durations will affect the Time-Aware efficiency.
 However, it will not affect the optimal value of the Time-Aware frame length
 as shown in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:simple differentiation"

\end_inset

, because increasing the frame length will increase the idle time which
 will worse the reading efficiency, and decreasing the value of the frame
 length will increase the collided time which will worse the reading efficiency,
 too.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Frame size ct"

\end_inset

 shows results for a constant number of tags.
 The Time-Aware optimal frame length is inverse proportional to the slot
 duration constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 According to figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Frame size ct"

\end_inset

, if the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 which means that we have identical slot durations.
 Therefore the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{opt-TA}$
\end_inset

 will be identical to the conventional optimal frame length equal to the
 number of tags 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
NUMERICAL ANALYSIS FOR THE TIME-AWARE OPTIMAL FRAME LENGTH
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, a new value of the optimal frame length has to be calculated
 periodically at the beginning of each frame based on the new estimated
 number of the tags.
 Thus, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lopt comlex expresion"

\end_inset

 should be calculated many times during the reading time.
 However, it is a non-linear equation with the number of tags 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, which is time consuming.
 In this section, a numerical analysis is applied on the exact Time-Aware
 frame length given in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lopt comlex expresion"

\end_inset

 to find a time efficient equation with a linear relation to the number
 of tags 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Applying two dimensional Least Square Fitting on equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lopt comlex expresion"

\end_inset

 results a simple linear relation between the new frame length 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{opt-TA}$
\end_inset

 and the number of tags:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{_{opt-TA-Aprox}}=(9.8C_{t}^{4}-26.6C_{t}^{3}+26.6C_{t}^{2}-12.3C_{t}+3.5)n\label{eq:Lopt aprox}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{footnotesize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lopt aprox"

\end_inset

 is a function of the slot duration constant (
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

) and the number of tags 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 The constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 depends on the standard, so it is calculated only once during the manufacturing
 of the reader based on the slot durations given in the standard.
 So it is a linear function of the estimated number of tags 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 which make the calculations simple and fast.
 It is also clear in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lopt aprox"

\end_inset

 that if we neglect the differences in slot durations (
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}=1$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{_{opt-TA-Aprox}}$
\end_inset

 will be identical to the conventional optimal frame length.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Curve fitting"

\end_inset

 clarifies how precise is the approximate frame length compared to the exact
 solution for a different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

.
