\begin_layout Section
RESULTS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Saving-time-versus"

\end_inset

 shows the effect of the proposed Time-Aware frame length on the percentage
 of saving in reading time versus all possible values of the slot duration
 constant (
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

).
 It is assumed in this simulation that the number of tags is well known,
 which means that we always work with the maximum efficiency.
 The definition of the reading time here is the time required by the reader
 to identify all tags in the interrogation area.
 The slot duration constant (
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

) is the ratio between the idle slot duration time and the collided slot
 duration time 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{t_{e}}{t_{c}}$
\end_inset

.
 In practice the idle slot duration time is shorter than the collided slot
 duration time, and the ration between them depends on the standard and
 the constrains of the application.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}=0$
\end_inset

, it means that the idle slot duration time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{e}$
\end_inset

 is quite small with respect to the collided slot duration time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the saving in reading time using the proposed Time-Aware
 frame length can reach up to 
\begin_inset Formula $12\%$
\end_inset

 from the conventional reading time, which uses the conventional calculations
 of the frame length.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}=1$
\end_inset

, which means that the slot durations are equal and we go towards the convention
al calculations of the reading efficiency, there is no saving time.
 According to the results in section IV, the slot duration constant for
 ISO 18000-6C standard 
\begin_inset Formula $(C_{t}$
\end_inset

) is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.2$
\end_inset

.
 In this case the saving in the reading time will be 
\begin_inset Formula $5.5\%$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, the number of tags in the interrogation region is unknown,
 so the anti-collision algorithms in RFID systems consist of two stages:
 1) Estimating the number of tags in the interrogation area.
 2) Calculating the optimal frame length to maximize the reading efficiency.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Percentage-of-Time"

\end_inset

 shows the percentages of saving in reading time using the proposed Time-Aware
 frame length for the two popular anti-collision algorithms Lower bound
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aloha4_Vogt"

\end_inset

, and Schoute 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DFSA_shoute_Random"

\end_inset

.
 Each one of these algorithms has a different basic tag estimation technique.
 The main issue of this simulation is to prove that the proposed Time-Aware
 frame length also can be applied in practical anti-collision protocols.
 Simulations in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Percentage-of-Time"

\end_inset

 use the ISO 18000-6C protocol.
 In this protocol, the frame lengths is allowed only to have discrete values
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{Q}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is a constant assigned by the reader.
 This quantization is the reason of the existence of some oscillations in
 the curve.
 According to the previous section, the slot duration constant for these
 simulations is 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}=0.2$
\end_inset

.
 Based on figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Percentage-of-Time"

\end_inset

, the average time saving for both anti-collision algorithms after the estimatio
n errors and using the proposed Time-Aware Frame Slotted Aloha (TAFSA) technique
 is around 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
CONCLUSION
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This Letter proposes a new optimization method to calculate the optimal
 frame size for frame slotted ALOHA anti-collision algorithms for RFID systems.
 The proposed method considers the differences of the slot durations.
 The reading time using the proposed Time-Aware frame length 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{opt-TA}$
\end_inset

 is lower than the reading time using the conventional frame length.
 This new Time-Aware frame length is applied on two different anti-collision
 algorithms and proves that it can decrease the reading time around 10%
 compared to the reading time using the conventional frame length.
 
\end_layout

